12.3.3 Exercises

  1. pivot_longer() and pivot_wider() are not perfectly symmetrical because pivot_wider() gets rid of the original column names and pivot_longer() does not know the column names.

  2. This code fails because 1999 and 2000 need to have backticks, otherwise R will read them as column numbers, not variable names.

  3. Widening this table fails because the name and names columns are not uniquely different rows.

people <- tribble(
  ~name,             ~names,  ~values,
  #-----------------|--------|------
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       45,
  "Phillip Woods",   "height",   186,
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       50,
  "Jessica Cordero", "age",       37,
  "Jessica Cordero", "height",   156
)

You can add a new column to uniquely identify each value like this:

people2 <- people %>%
  group_by(name, names) %>%
  mutate(obs = row_number())
people2
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
## # Groups:   name, names [4]
##   name            names  values   obs
##   <chr>           <chr>   <dbl> <int>
## 1 Phillip Woods   age        45     1
## 2 Phillip Woods   height    186     1
## 3 Phillip Woods   age        50     2
## 4 Jessica Cordero age        37     1
## 5 Jessica Cordero height    156     1
preg <- tribble(
  ~pregnant, ~male, ~female,
  "yes",     NA,    10,
  "no",      20,    12

You need to make it longer. The variables are gender, pregnant and count.

preg_tidy <- preg %>%

  1. The remove argument gets rid of original columns in the final dataframe. You would set it to FALSE if you want to keep the original columns when creating new ones.

  2. Separate() splits one column into a few. Extract() specifies variables in one column to split into a few. There are different ways to separate columns, but only one way to unite them.

12.5 Missing values

Example of missing data:

stocks <- tibble(
  year   = c(2015, 2015, 2015, 2015, 2016, 2016, 2016),
  qtr    = c(   1,    2,    3,    4,    2,    3,    4),
  return = c(1.88, 0.59, 0.35,   NA, 0.92, 0.17, 2.66)
)

Make the implicit values explicit:

stocks %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = return)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##     qtr `2015` `2016`
##   <dbl>  <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1     1   1.88  NA   
## 2     2   0.59   0.92
## 3     3   0.35   0.17
## 4     4  NA      2.66

Make explicit values implicit:

stocks %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = return) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(`2015`, `2016`),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "return",
    values_drop_na = TRUE
  )
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##     qtr year  return
##   <dbl> <chr>  <dbl>
## 1     1 2015    1.88
## 2     2 2015    0.59
## 3     2 2016    0.92
## 4     3 2015    0.35
## 5     3 2016    0.17
## 6     4 2016    2.66

Make missing values explicit using complete():

stocks %>%
  complete(year, qtr)
## # A tibble: 8 x 3
##    year   qtr return
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  2015     1   1.88
## 2  2015     2   0.59
## 3  2015     3   0.35
## 4  2015     4  NA   
## 5  2016     1  NA   
## 6  2016     2   0.92
## 7  2016     3   0.17
## 8  2016     4   2.66

Use when missing values indicate that a previous value should be carried forward:

treatment <- tribble(
  ~ person, ~ treatment, ~response,
  "Derrick Whitmore", 1, 7, 
  NA, 2, 10, 
  NA, 3, 9, 
  "Katherine Burke", 1, 4
)

Fill in missing values with fill():

treatment %>%
  fill(person)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   person           treatment response
##   <chr>                <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 Derrick Whitmore         1        7
## 2 Derrick Whitmore         2       10
## 3 Derrick Whitmore         3        9
## 4 Katherine Burke          1        4

12.5.1 Exercises

  1. Complete() enters explicit NAs into the dataset after finding all unique combinations in a set of columns and comparing them to the original dataset.

pivot_wider() makes long table shorter and wider when an observation is scattered across multiple rows.

fill() replaces missing values in a set of columns with the most recent non-missing values.

fill() and complete() put values (or NAs) into the dataset to make it complete and make missing values explicit. pivot_wider() organizes the dataset.

  1. The direction argument to fill() replaces missing values in a set of columns with the most recent non-missing values.

5.2.1 Comparisons

Make sure to use == not =:

Another potential error is floating point numbers:

sqrt(2) ^ 2 == 2
## [1] FALSE

Use near() instead of ==:

near(sqrt(2) ^ 2, 2)
## [1] TRUE

5.2.3 Missing Values

NA represents an unknown value and makes any operation involving an unknown value explicitly unknown:

NA > 5
## [1] NA
10 == NA
## [1] NA
NA + 10
## [1] NA
NA / 2
## [1] NA

Most confusing result:

NA == NA
## [1] NA
x <- NA
y <- NA
x == y
## [1] NA

Determine if a value is missing by using is.na():

is.na(x)
## [1] TRUE

Preserve missing values by asking for them explicity:

df <- tibble(x = c(1, NA, 3))
filter(df, x > 1)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       x
##   <dbl>
## 1     3

5.2.4.4

NA^0
## [1] 1
NA | TRUE
## [1] TRUE

This is true because the value of the missing value is true. Same for false:

NA & FALSE
## [1] FALSE
NA | FALSE
## [1] NA
NA & TRUE
## [1] NA
Inf * 0
## [1] NaN
-Inf * 0
## [1] NaN

NA * 0 is not equal to 0 because inf and -inf is undefined. NaN means not a number.

5.5.2 Exercises

  1. Divide dep_time by 100 to get the hours since midnight. Multiply by 60 and add the remainder of dep_time divided by 100. 1504, or 3:04 PM, is an example:
1504 %/% 100
## [1] 15
1504 %% 100
## [1] 4
1504 %/% 100 * 60 + 1504 %% 100
## [1] 904
  1. air_time is the amount of time in air; arr_time is the time the flight arrived and dep_time is the time the flight departed.
flights_airtime <-
  mutate(flights,
    dep_time = (dep_time %/% 100 * 60 + dep_time %% 100) %% 1440,
    arr_time = (arr_time %/% 100 * 60 + arr_time %% 100) %% 1440,
    air_time_diff = air_time - arr_time + dep_time
  )
nrow(filter(flights_airtime, air_time_diff !=0))
## [1] 327150

  1. dep_delay should be the same as the difference between sched_dep_time and dep_delay.

rankme <- tibble(
  x = c(10, 5, 1, 5, 5)

                 x_row_number = row_number(x),

The minrank() function assigns a rank to the number of values less than each set of tied values plus one.

flights_delayed <- mutate(flights,
  dep_delay_min_rank = min_rank(desc(dep_delay)),
  dep_delay_row_number = row_number(desc(dep_delay)),
  dep_delay_dense_rank = dense_rank(desc(dep_delay))
)
flights_delayed <- filter(
  flights_delayed,
  !(dep_delay_min_rank > 10 | dep_delay_row_number > 10 |
    dep_delay_dense_rank > 10)
)
flights_delayed <- arrange(flights_delayed, dep_delay_min_rank)
print(select(
  flights_delayed, month, day, carrier, flight, dep_delay,
  dep_delay_min_rank, dep_delay_row_number, dep_delay_dense_rank
),
n = Inf
)

## length
##  [1]  2  4  6  5  7  9  8 10 12 11

This returns a warning, because adding 2 vectors recycles the shorter vectors values to get vectors of the same length.

  1. All trigonometric functions are available in Trig. This includes sine, cosine, and tangent.

5.6.1 Combining multiple operations with the pipe

Explore relationship between distance and average delay:

by_dest <- group_by(flights, dest)
delay <- summarise(by_dest,
                   count = n(),
                   dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),
                   delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
delay <- filter(delay, count > 20, dest != "HNL")
ggplot(data = delay, mapping = aes(x = dist, y = delay)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = count), alpha = 1/3) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Use pipe instead:

delays <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),
    delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  filter(count > 20, dest != "HNL")

  filter(n >= 20) %>%
  filter(min_rank(on_time) == 1)

standardized_flights <- flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(air_time)) %>%
  group_by(dest, origin) %>%
  mutate(
    air_time_mean = mean(air_time),
    air_time_sd = sd(air_time),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(air_time_standard = (air_time - air_time_mean) / (air_time_sd + 1))
standardized_flights %>%
  arrange(air_time_standard) %>%
  select(
    carrier, flight, origin, dest, month, day,

  arrange(tailnum, year, month, day) %>%
